        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4682.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. D. Hooker, 26 November [1864]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4140.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Edward Sabine</ref>, president of the <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4110.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Royal Society of London</ref>, wrote the anniversary address delivered at the 30 November 1864 meeting of the Society (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6833.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Sabine 1864</ref>). See also <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4688.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from E. A. Darwin, [before 30 November 1864]</ref> and n. 4.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4682.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. D. Hooker, 26 November [1864]</ref> and n. 16. CD cited Hooker’s observations of <hi rend="italic">Wistaria</hi> (also called <hi rend="italic">Wisteria</hi>) in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1456.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">‘Climbing plants’</ref>, pp. 21–2. See also <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4692.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. D. Hooker, 2 December 1864</ref>, and n. 10.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">Hooker refers to the Muséum d’Histoire Naturelle in Paris. Hooker may have seen the trees when he visited <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_3492.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Charles Victor Naudin</ref>, who was an aide-naturaliste at the Muséum, in January 1863 (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 11, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-3940.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. D. Hooker, 24 January 1863</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4658.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Charles Lyell, 4 November 1864</ref> and n. 3, and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4682.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. D. Hooker, 26 November [1864]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">Hooker refers to the physicians <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4976.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Thomas Watson</ref> (aged 72) and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_68.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">James Alderson</ref> (aged 70).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f7">Hooker refers to part 4 of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_793.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Boott 1858–67</ref>. See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4667.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. D. Hooker, [23 November 1864]</ref> and n. 13, and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4682.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. D. Hooker, 26 November [1864]</ref> and n. 10.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f8">Hooker’s uncle, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4823.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Dawson William Turner</ref>, was a well-known philanthropist (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2063.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">DNB</hi></ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f9">Hooker refers to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_4735.xml">Thomas Thomson</ref>, who had been superintendent of the Calcutta botanic garden between 1854 and 1860 or 1861 (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2063.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">DNB</hi></ref>, <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1985.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">R. Desmond 1994</ref>). CD cited Thomson and Hooker on <hi rend="italic">Butea parviflora</hi> (a synonym of <hi rend="italic">Spatholobus parviflorus</hi>) and other tropical climbers in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1456.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">‘Climbing plants’</ref>, p. 22.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f10"><hi rend="italic">Sua sponte</hi>: ‘of its own accord’. CD cited Hooker on <hi rend="italic">Ruscus androgynus</hi> in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1456.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">‘Climbing plants’</ref>, p. 21. CD’s notes on <hi rend="italic">Ruscus androgynus</hi> are in DAR 157.1: 21. See also <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4692.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from J. D. Hooker, 2 December 1864</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f11">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-4682.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. D. Hooker, 26 November [1864]</ref> and n. 14.</note>
        </div>        
            
